Current State of AthenAI — Plain English Walkthrough
What Has Been Built
The project has a complete, well-organized inference pipeline. Think of it as a fully assembled car with no fuel and no engine break-in — it has all the right parts in the right places, but it has never actually run on real data.

Here's what each piece does:

Audio Encoder: Takes noisy speech, converts it to patches (like cutting a spectrogram into a grid of tiles), and produces a sequence of embedding vectors representing what was said
Sensor Encoder: Takes 8 industrial sensor readings over time and compresses them into a single embedding vector representing the machine's current state
Fusion Module: Uses cross-attention so the sensor context can "modulate" the speech understanding — for example, if pressure is spiking, the model should favor "increase pressure" or "decrease pressure" as the likely command
Classifier: Takes the fused embedding and outputs one of 20 safety commands, plus a confidence score and entropy-based uncertainty
Synthesizer: Once a command is identified, generates a clean audio clip of that command using Meta's AudioGen
Alert Generator: Sends the command + confidence to an LLM and gets back a structured safety alert for the operator
The two-mode design (base vs full) is smart — it lets you deploy audio-only when sensors aren't available, and the full multimodal system when they are.

The Big Problem: The Audio Encoder Is Not What It Claims To Be
This is the most important thing to understand. The file src/encoders/audio_jepa.py is called "Audio-JEPA" but it is not a JEPA implementation. Here's why that matters:

What JEPA actually does: It trains an encoder by masking parts of the input (like hiding 50% of a spectrogram) and making the model predict the embedding of the hidden parts from the visible parts. This is why JEPA encoders are particularly good at noisy audio — they learn to infer meaning from incomplete, corrupted signals.

What the current code actually does: It loads a ViT that was pretrained on ImageNet (photos of dogs, cars, flowers) and repurposes it for mel-spectrograms via a patch embedding layer. An EMA target encoder exists in the code but is never called during inference. There is no masking, no predictor, no JEPA training.

This isn't broken — the ViT will still produce useful audio embeddings. But it won't have the noise robustness that a properly trained audio JEPA would provide.

Where to Begin and How to Start Training
The training roadmap has 5 steps, in order:

Set up the environment — install dependencies, verify GPU
Get the data — download Google Speech Commands (for speech), MS-SNSD (for industrial noise), SKAB (for sensor readings)
Replace the audio encoder — swap the ImageNet ViT for WavJEPA-Nat-Base, a true JEPA encoder with pretrained weights that was specifically trained for noisy environments
Build the data mixing pipeline — write code to combine speech + noise at different SNR levels and pair with sensor readings
Train and evaluate — train the fusion + classifier layers while keeping the audio encoder frozen (transfer learning)
The Audio-JEPA Resources You Found
Sony CSL (audio-representations): Cannot be used. The author accidentally deleted the pretrained weights and has left the project entirely. You can read their code for architectural ideas, but there's nothing to download or run.

WavJEPA (labhamlet/wavjepa): This is the one you want. Specifically labhamlet/wavjepa-nat-base. It is:

A true JEPA architecture (waveform → ViT context encoder + EMA target encoder + ViT predictor)
Pretrained on AudioSet (1.74M audio clips)
Additionally trained with 85,000 simulated noisy room environments (SNR 5–40 dB) — the closest published training condition to your industrial scenario
0.2B parameters, MIT licensed, Transformers-compatible, actively maintained (November 2025)
Takes raw 16kHz waveforms as input (simpler than mel-spectrogram preprocessing)
This replaces your current AudioJEPAEncoder and requires only three pipeline adjustments: remove mel-spec preprocessing, update the encoder loading code, update the import. Everything else stays the same.

